  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect through various mechanisms and frameworks designed to prevent, detect, and prosecute financial crimes. Here are some key aspects of this intersection:\n\n1. International Standards and Conventions\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Palermo Convention\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- These provide standardized approaches for combating money laundering\n\n2. Legal Cooperation Mechanisms\n- Mutual Legal Assistance Treaties (MLATs)\n- Information sharing between financial intelligence units\n- Extradition agreements\n- Cross-border investigations and prosecutions\n\n3. Regulatory Compliance Requirements\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious Transaction Reporting\n- Customer due diligence protocols\n- Implemented through national legislation consistent with international standards\n\n4. Jurisdictional Harmonization\n- Countries adapting domestic laws to align with international best practices\n- Consistent definitions of money laundering offenses\n- Standardized reporting and investigation procedures\n\n5. Enforcement and Sanctions\n- International financial sanctions\n- Asset freezing mechanisms\n- Coordinated efforts to track and disrupt illicit financial flows\n\nThis complex system aims to create a comprehensive global approach to combating financial crimes.",
